                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d850">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/12–1048: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cabot</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-12-10T13:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 10, 1948—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 10—2:38 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2724. British Consul in speech Rotary Club played down possibility of disorders
                    and consequent need for evacuation of Shanghai. He rather strongly intimated
                    that all Britishers, except perhaps young children, should stay.</p>
                <p>Sent Nanking 2043; repeated Department 2724.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cabot</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
